		<td>
	




CEA President and CEO Gary Shapiro welcomed Sun Microsystems Chairman and CEO Scott McNealy saying information technology and home networking are vital components of CES, and Sun Microsystems has been an innovator in both.
<p>
 	Scott McNealy's global company offers end-to-end solutions for doing business in the network age. With its platform-independent Java and Jini technologies, Sun provides high-speed microprocessors, scalable systems, robust software, network storage, mission-critical support and comprehensive professional services --all the key components that drive the Internet as well as corporate intranets and business-to-business extranets. 
<p>
McNealy said that the 18-year-old Sun Microsystems is well known for pushing the envelope in a .com world and now has revenues topping $12 billion. He has always been willing to share his ideas…and hopes today to leave them laughing and thinking and wanting more from technology and him.
<p>
An onstage skit took place at the "Customer Return Desk" where a customer attempted to return his outdated electronic items. McNealy took down the sign "Customer Returns" and hung a new sign saying "Simply Connect." The only way to accomplish this, he said, is to have everything speak the same language.  He said they have thought about this fact at Sun.  "If you walk out there on the floor, you will notice that the world has more things than people. The average home has 50 CPUs. The real Internet opportunity before us is networking things. That is the big challenge. They all have different operating systems and they need to talk. The computer industry is behind in this area. The industry has lost the focus on simplicity and reliability."
<p>


	
		
	



